In the process of upgrading our shooter mechanism using a few Kraken motors.
The mechanism is (hopefully) going to be an LRU and the lengths from the PDH to the Krakens is longer than the lengths that come with the Kraken.

I know we could run a single length and connect to the Kraken ring connector - but has anyone used an inline connector like a Wago or Anderson for these 10 AwG power wires?
If so - what did you use?

This past year, we used Anderson Connectors with these crimp terminals which work for the 10 AWG wire: 261G3 Anderson Power Products, Inc. | Connectors, Interconnects | DigiKey

The standard Anderson Housings also work with these crimp connectors:

  • 1327-BK Anderson Power Products, Inc. | Connectors, Interconnects | DigiKey
  • 1327G6-BK Anderson Power Products, Inc. | Connectors, Interconnects | DigiKey

The typical WAGO 221-2401 inline lever-nut will not work with the wire included with the Krakens, we know from experience. The next size up lever nuts do fit, but there is not an inline version. The 221-612 worked well for us on the fine-stranded, silicone-insulated 10 AWG wire that shipped with the Kraken, though admittedly I haven’t inspected the connections personally.

Alright - I’m recommending that we bite the bullet and run new power cables (10AWG) from the PDH, up through are energy chain, and to the 4 Krakens we’re going to use.
More work overall than a new suitable 10AWG inline connection to the wires already there for Falcons - but more reliable in the long run.

While we’re testing this new shooter config - I might use these as a short term connection:

Amazon.com: Posi-lock Connectors, 10-12 Gauge, Bulk Pack of 20 : Automotive

The standard Anderson Housings also work with these crimp connectors:

Did you end up having to strip the insulation further back to get them into the housing? We couldn’t easily fit the 10awg wire that came with the Kraken in our housings so we stripped slightly further back and electrical taped/heat shrinked around them. We always buy our crimps and housings from Powerwerx, wondering if there’s any size differences.

Going with a thinner insulation wire that meets the 10ga target would likely be the way to go.

We’ve been using Anderson Powerpole connectors for years. This year, the only Anderson connector on our robot is the SB120 for our battery.

All of our Kraken power connections are point-to-point from PDH to the Ring Terminals on the Kraken. We crimp our own ring terminals when needed for the extra power cable length.

Power: McMaster-Carr

How do you connect the CAN wires to each other?

Either Anderson connectors or Wago 221-612 will work for 10 awg wire. Wagos are nice because they are easier, cheaper, and require a bit less care to do right (I’ve not used them for power personally but that’s my impression). However they are not inline, and sometimes the ability to edit connections is nice.

By my calculations, over 4ft of length, 2AWG has maybe about 1 milliOhm less resistance than 6AWG. So, if you’re pulling 400 Amps during hard acceleration, your voltage drop across the 4ft of 2AWG wire would be 0.4V less than the voltage drop across an equal length of 6AWG wire. Potentially meaningful I suppose if you’re close to a brownout threshold.
